    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "python3 - <<'PY'\nimport json\nd = json.load(open(\"/home/anup/.claude/projects/-home-anup-claude-projects-stm32-substrate-tests-fixtures-projects-F-PROJ-NUCLEO-L476RG/3c0778bf-5ea1-47e9-92a0-ee956e3a0a36/tool-results/b4veo26l8.txt\"))\nfor reg in (\"APB1ENR1\", \"APB1RSTR1\", \"CCIPR\", \"CFGR\"):\n    r = d[\"registers\"].get(reg)\n    if not r: continue\n    print(reg, \"raw=0x%08X\" % r[\"raw_value\"])\n    for f, v in r[\"fields\"].items():\n        if \"USART2\" in f or f in (\"SW\",\"SWS\"):\n            print(\"   \", f, \"=\", v[\"raw_value\"], v.get(\"enum_name\"))\nPY",
        "description": "Extract USART2-related RCC fields from dump"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "Multiple probes are attached \u2014 gdbserver refused to pick one. Listing probes to select the right serial:\nProject targets the NUCLEO-L476RG (probe `066DFF...`). Reading RCC with that probe pinned:\n**Yes \u2014 the USART2 clock is enabled.** The RCC enable bit was not forgotten. Read live from the L476 (attach without reset, so this is the firmware's actual state):\n\n| RCC field | Value | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| `APB1ENR1.USART2EN` | **1** | USART2 peripheral clock **enabled** (it's the only bit set in APB1ENR1, raw `0x00020000`) |\n| `APB1RSTR1.USART2RST` | 0 | Not held in reset |\n| `CCIPR.USART2SEL` | 0 = PCLK1 | Kernel clock sourced from APB1 bus clock |\n| `CFGR.SW/SWS` | 3 | System clock running off PLL (PLLON/PLLRDY = 1), so PCLK1 is live |\n\nSo the clock tree is fine end-to-end: PLL is up, APB1 is clocked, USART2EN is set, and the kernel clock mux points at PCLK1.\n\nIf USART2 still isn't behaving, the clock isn't your culprit \u2014 next suspects would be:\n- **GPIO**: `GPIOAEN` in `AHB2ENR` + PA2/PA3 set to AF7 (I can dump `GPIOA` next)\n- **USART2 itself**: `CR1.UE`/`TE`/`RE` and `BRR` baud value (`stm32 debug read-peripheral USART USART2`)\n\nWant me to check either of those?"
}